1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Let's start by defining what is the session.

2
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Well, let's start by defining what is the session.

3
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:46,000
Well, when a user logs into a system, when they've properly identified themselves, when they've authenticated themselves,

4
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:51,000
and they've been authorized into the system, that begins what is known as a session.

5
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:56,000
And we want to manage these sessions. We want to make sure that these sessions are secure.

6
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:01,000
Because one of the major things we want to watch out for is something called session hijacking.

7
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Session hijacking is where an attacker, a baddie, somehow takes over a user session.

8
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
And a session, of course, means that the user is authenticated. They have access to the system.

9
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:16,000
So if someone takes over hijacks your session, it means that they would have the same rights as you.

10
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,000
There's a bunch of different ways of conducting session hijacking.

11
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:27,000
It can be very complicated. It can also be very simple. For instance, if I were to log into my laptop and then walk away,

12
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:32,000
while my laptop is still logged in, and someone else was to come up to my laptop and start using a laptop,

13
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
what have they done with my session? They have hijacked it.

14
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:42,000
So it can be as simple as that. It can also be very complicated, hijacking, VPN sessions, all sorts of things like that.

15
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Here's a good question. What's the very best way of preventing session hijacking?

16
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:54,000
Well, the very best way is to actually force reauthentication.

17
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:57,000
So if your screensaver comes up and requires you to log back in,

18
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:00,000
if you require someone to put in their password again,

19
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:05,000
it's going to, if you terminate the session and then require someone to reauthenticate,

20
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:08,000
anyone that had hijacked the session has now lost access.

21
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:12,000
So the perfect answer of how we prevent session hijacking is very simple.

22
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:15,000
It's actually to force reauthentication.

23
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
And if you're really concerned about high session hijacking, you might even move to almost continuous reauthentication.

24
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:25,000
For example, some VPN solutions are actually doing this behind the scenes,

25
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:32,000
without us even realizing they're constantly reauthenticating to trying to prevent something like session hijacking.

26
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:38,000
Now let's talk about some of the different methods that we use for managing sessions.

27
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:41,000
The first one, known as schedule limitations,

28
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:45,000
actually controls when you're allowed to open or create a session.

29
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:52,000
So the idea here is that if an organization's employees all work from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m. Monday through Friday,

30
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:59,000
then schedule limitations could be set up to only allow users to create a session to log in to their system

31
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
between, say, 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. Monday through Friday.

32
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:08,000
If someone tried it Saturday night at 2 a.m., they would just be blocked.

33
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
They would say, nope, session cannot be created right now.

34
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
So that's the idea of session limitations.

35
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
The next one is log in limitations.

36
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,000
And this goes back to this idea that we never want to have shared accounts.

37
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
We want to have one account to one user.

38
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And that one user should only be logged in once because they have one system.

39
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:34,000
So log in limitation is about only letting a user log in with a certain set of credentials once.

40
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:40,000
And if someone else is trying to log in with the same credentials, then you know that's a problem.

41
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Next is timeouts.

42
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:44,000
And we use timeouts all the time.

43
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:47,000
Perfect example is your screensaver.

44
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Your screensaver is usually set for something like 5 minutes.

45
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,000
And at 5 minutes of inactivity, what happens?

46
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,000
Well, your screensaver comes up.

47
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
And when you go back to the system and you try and you jiggle the mouse,

48
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
you get the screensaver to go away.

49
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Before you can use the system again, what do you have to do?

50
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:05,000
Log in.

51
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
So this is an example of session timeout.

52
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
And lots of different systems do this, like an online banking system, for instance.

53
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:15,000
Well, often like log you out after 5 minutes of inactivity.

54
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,000
Now, let's talk about registration or the idea of identity proofing.

55
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:25,000
So identity proofing is this concept that when a new employee joins the organization,

56
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
you want to make sure that they actually are who they say they are.

57
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:29,000
You've done interviews.

58
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,000
You've done background checks.

59
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
You've made sure that this is the perfect employee for your organization.

60
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:37,000
But you want to make sure that when they actually show up on their first day of work,

61
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
that they are who they say they are, that you're giving out the badge, the credentials,

62
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:45,000
all the keys to the kingdom to the right person.

63
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,000
So how can we identity proof someone?

64
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:52,000
If they first show up for work, how can we confirm that they are who they say they are?

65
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:57,000
Well, one of the easiest ways of identity proofing someone is to ask for their government ID,

66
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
something like a driver's license or a passport.

67
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
So that's simply the concept of identity proofing.

68
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
We use it all sorts of places when someone first joins the organization.

69
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:11,000
We talked about it, we'll talk about it in relation to certificate authorities

70
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,000
and how a registration authority in RA will identity proof someone before they give them

71
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,000
a digital certificate.

72
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:20,000
So that's registration and identity proofing.

